<Layout title="Module 5 – Mobility & Transfer">
  <h1>Module 5: Mobility &amp; Transfer</h1>
  <p>
    Maintaining mobility is critical to preventing complications of immobility (pneumonia,
    DVT, pressure injuries, muscle atrophy) and promoting patient independence and recovery.
  </p>

  <h2>Body Mechanics</h2>
  <p>
    Proper body mechanics protect the nurse from musculoskeletal injury and facilitate safe
    patient handling.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Use a wide base of support; feet shoulder-width apart.</li>
    <li>Keep the load close to your body.</li>
    <li>Bend at the knees and hips, not the waist — engage your legs, not your back.</li>
    <li>Keep your spine in neutral alignment; avoid twisting.</li>
    <li>Push or pull rather than lift when possible.</li>
    <li>Use assistive devices (gait belts, slide boards, mechanical lifts) for patient transfers.</li>
    <li>Ask for assistance whenever needed — Safe Patient Handling policies require it for most lifts.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ Safety First</strong>
    Manual lifting of patients is a leading cause of nurse injury. Follow your facility's
    Safe Patient Handling and Mobility (SPHM) program; use mechanical lifts for dependent
    patients.
  </div>

  <h2>Effects of Immobility</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>System</th><th>Complications of Immobility</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Cardiovascular</td><td>Orthostatic hypotension, DVT, pulmonary embolism</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Respiratory</td><td>Atelectasis, hypostatic pneumonia, decreased lung expansion</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Musculoskeletal</td><td>Muscle atrophy, contractures, osteoporosis</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Integumentary</td><td>Pressure injuries, skin breakdown</td></tr>
      <tr><td>GI</td><td>Constipation, paralytic ileus</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Urinary</td><td>Urinary stasis, UTI, kidney stones</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Psychosocial</td><td>Depression, anxiety, social isolation, sensory deprivation</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Range-of-Motion (ROM) Exercises</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Active ROM:</strong> Patient moves joints independently — preferred when possible.</li>
    <li><strong>Active-assistive ROM:</strong> Nurse assists the patient in moving their own joints.</li>
    <li><strong>Passive ROM:</strong> Nurse moves the patient's joints — performed when the patient cannot participate.</li>
    <li>Perform ROM at least twice daily for immobile patients.</li>
    <li>Move each joint through its full range, smoothly and slowly.</li>
    <li>Stop if the patient reports pain; never force a joint past its pain-free range.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Transfer Techniques</h2>
  <h3>Bed to Chair (Two-Person Assist)</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Explain the procedure to the patient.</li>
    <li>Raise the bed to the lowest position; lock wheels.</li>
    <li>Place the chair at a 45° angle to the bed on the patient's stronger side.</li>
    <li>Apply a gait belt around the patient's waist.</li>
    <li>Assist patient to a sitting position; pause to assess for dizziness (orthostatic hypotension).</li>
    <li>Patient places hands on bed; nurse supports the patient at the gait belt.</li>
    <li>On count, pivot the patient to stand, then lower into chair.</li>
    <li>Ensure comfort and safety before leaving.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Using a Mechanical Lift</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Assess patient weight and select appropriate sling size/type.</li>
    <li>Position sling under patient per manufacturer instructions.</li>
    <li>Attach sling to lift frame; raise patient slightly to verify security.</li>
    <li>Move lift and lower patient into chair; remove sling or leave in place per facility policy.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Ambulation Assistance</h2>
  <h3>Pre-Ambulation Assessment</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Review physician orders and activity restrictions.</li>
    <li>Assess baseline vital signs; reassess after sitting and standing (orthostatic BP).</li>
    <li>Ensure non-skid footwear and appropriate clothing.</li>
    <li>Clear the pathway of IV poles, cords, and equipment.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Assisting with Ambulation</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Apply gait belt snugly around the patient's waist.</li>
    <li>Walk on the patient's weaker or affected side; hold the gait belt with an underhand grip at the back.</li>
    <li>Progress distance gradually based on patient tolerance.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Assistive Devices</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Device</th><th>Indication</th><th>Key Teaching Points</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Cane</td>
        <td>Mild imbalance or weakness on one side</td>
        <td>Hold on stronger side; move cane and weaker leg simultaneously</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Walker</td>
        <td>Bilateral weakness; poor balance</td>
        <td>Lift all four legs simultaneously (standard walker); never drag; patient steps inside frame</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Crutches</td>
        <td>Non-weight-bearing or partial weight-bearing on one extremity</td>
        <td>Weight through hands, not axilla; 2-inch gap from axilla; various gaits (2-point, 3-point, 4-point)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Crutch Measurement</strong>
    Top of crutch should be 2–3 finger-widths (about 4–5 cm) below the axilla with the
    patient standing upright. Handgrip should allow 20–30° elbow flexion.
  </div>

  <h2>Fall Prevention</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Complete a fall-risk assessment on admission and re-assess per protocol (e.g., Morse Fall Scale).</li>
    <li>Implement individualized fall-prevention interventions: bed alarm, non-skid socks, call light within reach, frequent rounding.</li>
    <li>Educate patient and family on fall risk and prevention strategies.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>DVT:</strong> Deep vein thrombosis — blood clot in a deep vein; major complication of immobility.</li>
    <li><strong>Atelectasis:</strong> Collapse of lung alveoli; caused by inadequate deep breathing in immobile patients.</li>
    <li><strong>Contracture:</strong> Permanent shortening of muscle or connective tissue from prolonged immobility.</li>
    <li><strong>Gait belt:</strong> Assistive device worn around the patient's waist to provide a secure grip during transfers and ambulation.</li>
    <li><strong>SPHM:</strong> Safe Patient Handling and Mobility program.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
